Reasoning: The claim that insomnia can be effectively treated with cognitive behavioral therapy is strongly supported by evidence from paper ID 5912283, "Cognitive behavioral therapy vs zopiclone for treatment of chronic primary insomnia in older adults: a randomized controlled trial." This study, a randomized, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trial, found that Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) led to improved short- and long-term outcomes compared to zopiclone (a sleep medication) on 3 out of 4 outcome measures. Specifically, participants in the CBT group showed a significant improvement in sleep efficiency, from 81.4% at pretreatment to 90.1% at 6-month follow-up (prop_634), while the zopiclone group experienced a slight decrease in sleep efficiency (prop_635). The CBT group also spent more time in slow-wave sleep (prop_636). The study concluded that CBT interventions are superior to zopiclone for both short- and long-term management of insomnia in older adults. While the study design is robust, the paper has 0 citations and unknown author/year information, which slightly reduces the overall confidence. No other directly corroborating papers were found in the knowledge base.
